<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-228-249 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 825 367</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Feb 1991 v16 n2 p285(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>XGA: a new graphics standard; combine a fast VGA, a graphicscoprocessor, and bus mastering. (IBM debuts its high-resolutionExtended Graphics Array display technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Richter, Jake.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM debuts its high-resolution Extended Graphics Array (XGA) videodisplay standard for Intel 80386- and 80486-based IBM PS/2microcomputer hardware.andP;  XGA solves many of the problems in IBM'sprevious 8514/A high-resolution display technology, includingbackward compatibility with the VGA graphics standard.andP;  Majorcomponents of an XGA product include dual-ported video,random-access memory (RAM), custom graphics coprocessor anddisplay controller chips, glue logic, and video-out connector.andO;The technology supports display modes to 1,024-by-768-pixels withup to 65,536 colors.andP;  Details of the initialization processing,display controller, task switching, defining drawing space,drawing with the XGA, and bus-mastering problems are discussed.andO;XGA will probably not affect the market for Super VGA or 8514/Aproducts in the near future.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     High ResolutionStandardsVideo DisplaySystem DesignTechnologySpecifications.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   Comparison of PS/2 VGA, Super VGA, 8514/A and XGA displaystandards. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>